00:01:14.348 --> 00:01:18.640
I think those of us who
treat patients with autism

00:01:18.640 --> 00:01:20.360
and certainly those of us doing research

00:01:20.360 --> 00:01:22.678
in autism spectrum disorders understand

00:01:22.678 --> 00:01:25.430
how complicated they are
and how heterogeneous

00:01:25.430 --> 00:01:27.850
they are in terms of presentation,

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:30.480
certainly in terms of etiology,

00:01:30.480 --> 00:01:33.273
and increasing in prevalence.

00:01:35.190 --> 00:01:37.410
Our research has really
tried to understand

00:01:37.410 --> 00:01:38.940
what are some of these etiologies?

00:01:38.940 --> 00:01:40.840
Can we identify biomarkers?

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:44.320
Can we find endophenotypes
or subtypes of autism

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:48.580
that help us in understanding
potential targeted treatments

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:51.720
so that we can do a better job

00:01:51.720 --> 00:01:56.270
in not only early diagnosis
but early treatment as well.

00:01:56.270 --> 00:01:57.103
So as I said,

00:01:57.103 --> 00:01:59.380
I'm gonna try and highlight
some translational research

00:01:59.380 --> 00:02:01.130
that's been ongoing at the Mind Institute,

00:02:01.130 --> 00:02:03.530
I realize for about 20 years,

00:02:03.530 --> 00:02:06.340
and some of the most recent research

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:08.630
that we have that primarily relates

00:02:08.630 --> 00:02:10.920
to looking at
gene-environment interactions

00:02:10.920 --> 00:02:15.340
as well as taking us
along this path to looking

00:02:15.340 --> 00:02:18.903
at immune dysregulation as
a risk factor in autism.

00:02:20.550 --> 00:02:22.860
So the learning objectives are one,

00:02:22.860 --> 00:02:25.270
to understand the current
prevalence estimates

00:02:25.270 --> 00:02:27.890
of autism in the United States,

00:02:27.890 --> 00:02:31.800
to understand or identify four maternal

00:02:31.800 --> 00:02:34.180
metabolic conditions
that we think increase

00:02:34.180 --> 00:02:35.710
the risk for autism as well

00:02:35.710 --> 00:02:38.363
as more generalized developmental delays.

00:02:39.200 --> 00:02:41.520
To understand or list the
clinical characteristics

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:43.790
of a subtype of autism called

00:02:43.790 --> 00:02:48.790
maternal auto-antibody
related autism or MAR autism,

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:51.670
and to list some of the
core and co-morbid symptoms

00:02:51.670 --> 00:02:53.910
associated with some different immune

00:02:53.910 --> 00:02:56.563
endophenotypes in the children themselves.

00:02:59.130 --> 00:03:02.020
So we are fortunate in the United States

00:03:02.020 --> 00:03:06.040
to have the CDC doing
ongoing prevalence studies

00:03:06.040 --> 00:03:08.540
across the country at various sites,

00:03:08.540 --> 00:03:11.180
and each time that they report out,

00:03:11.180 --> 00:03:13.100
which is about every two years,

00:03:13.100 --> 00:03:16.200
the prevalence of autism has increased

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:18.240
and we don't know how much longer

00:03:18.240 --> 00:03:19.300
it's going to keep increasing,

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:24.300
but right now it's currently
one in 59 or 1.7% of children,

00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:28.410
and this work is done where they evaluate

00:03:28.410 --> 00:03:30.893
multiple records at eight years of age.

00:03:31.910 --> 00:03:33.730
So it's up from the last
time they reported it,

00:03:33.730 --> 00:03:35.283
which was one in 68,

00:03:36.170 --> 00:03:38.450
and one thing I think is significant

00:03:38.450 --> 00:03:40.201
is that less than half of these children,

00:03:40.201 --> 00:03:44.330
looking back, were diagnosed by age four,

00:03:44.330 --> 00:03:47.300
although most of their parents
had concerns way before this.

00:03:47.300 --> 00:03:49.620
I think it really pushes us to try

00:03:49.620 --> 00:03:51.640
and figure out ways to
do earlier diagnosis

00:03:51.640 --> 00:03:53.623
so we can really get earlier treatment.

00:03:55.210 --> 00:03:58.100
This is a schematic
just to start the story

00:03:58.100 --> 00:04:00.870
of the research that we've been doing

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:04.160
and I'm not quite sure
